The '''General Administration of Quality Supervision, Inspection and Quarantine of the People's Republic of China''' ({{lang-zh|中华人民共和国国家质量监督检验检疫总局}}, abbreviated '''AQSIQ''') is a ministerial-level department under the [[State Council of the People's Republic of China]] that is in charge of [[quality control|national quality]], [[metrology]], entry-exit commodity inspection, entry-exit health [[quarantine]], entry-exit animal and plant quarantine, import-export [[food safety]], [[certification]] and [[accreditation]], [[standardization]], as well as administrative [[Law enforcement agency|law enforcement]].
AQSIQ directly administers provincial '''Entry-Exit Inspection and Quarantine Bureaus''' and '''Bureaus of Quality and Technical Supervision'''.<ref>Links to local bureaus are available on the official web site at http://english.aqsiq.gov.cn/</ref> For example, the '''Beijing Entry-Exit Inspection and Quarantine Bureau''' is responsible for collecting health declaration forms, and used thermal imaging to spot passengers with fever due to the [[2009 flu pandemic]] prior to July 16, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iata.org/NR/rdonlyres/019A193B-9C00-4062-A48A-A4AD4D5172A5/0/China.pdf|title=People's Republic of China:Known measures adopted following the A (H1N1) Flu outbreak|publisher=International Air Transport Association|date=2009-07-17}}</ref>
