{{Infobox technology standard | title = Networked Help Desk | image = [[File:Networked_Help_Desk_Logo.jpg]] | caption = Networked Help Desk logo | first_published = June 2011 | version = 1.0<ref name="RFC">{{cite web |title=The Networked Help Desk 1.0 Protocol |date=2011-06-01 |url=http://networkedhelpdesk.org/rfc/ |accessdate=2016-05-06}}</ref> | organization = [[Zendesk]] | committee = | editors = | authors = | base_standards = [[Hypertext Transfer Protocol|HTTP]], [[JSON]], [[Representational state transfer|REST]]<ref name="RFC"/> | related_standards = [[Java Community Process|JSR]] 91: [[Operations support system|OSS]] Trouble Ticket API<ref name="JSR91">{{cite web |title=The Java Community Process(SM) Program - JSRs: Java Specification Requests - detail JSR# 091 |url=https://jcp.org/en/jsr/detail?id=091 |date=2007-08-21}}</ref> | abbreviation = NHD | domain = Issue tracking, Bug tracking, Customer relationship management, Project management.<ref name="RFC">{{cite web |title=The Networked Help Desk 1.0 Protocol |date=2011-06-01 |url=http://networkedhelpdesk.org/rfc/ |accessdate=2016-05-06}}</ref> | license = | website = {{URL|networkedhelpdesk.org}} }}
'''Networked Help Desk''' is an [[open standard]] initiative to provide a common [[Application programming interface|API]] for sharing customer support tickets between separate instances of [[Issue tracking system|issue tracking]], [[Bug tracking system|bug tracking]], [[customer relationship management]] (CRM) and [[Project management software|project management]] systems to improve [[customer service]] and reduce [[vendor lock-in]].<ref name="NHDMAIN">{{cite web |title=Open Standard for Customer Service and Help Desks |date=2011-06-01 |url=http://networkedhelpdesk.org/}}</ref><ref name="ASAY2011">{{cite journal |title=One help desk API to unite them all: Down with the Software Tower of Babel |date=2011-06-01 |last=Asay |first=Matt |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2011/07/01/networking_the_helpdesk/ |accessdate=2016-05-06 |journal=[[The Register]]}}</ref> The initiative was created by [[Zendesk]] in June 2011 in collaboration with eight other founding member organizations including [[Atlassian]], [[New Relic]], [[OTRS]], [[Pivotal Tracker]], [[ServiceNow]] and [[SugarCRM]].<ref name="CARR2011">{{cite journal |title=Help Desk Shuffle: Will New Standard Help? |date=2011-06-07 |first=David F. |last=Carr |url=http://www.informationweek.com/crm/help-desk-shuffle-will-new-standard-help/d/d-id/1098166 |accessdate=2016-05-06 |journal=[[InformationWeek]]}}</ref><ref name="MEMBERS">{{cite web |title=Networked Help Desk Members |url=http://networkedhelpdesk.org/members/ |accessdate=2016-05-06}}</ref> The first integration, between Zendesk and Atlassian's issue tracking product, [[Jira (software)|JIRA]],<ref name="CARR2011"/> was announced at the 2011 Atlassian Summit.<ref name="LATKIEWICZ2011B">{{cite news |first=Matthew |last=Latkiewicz |date=2011-06-07 |title=Zendesk's JIRA Integration Rocks! |url=https://www.zendesk.com/blog/zendesks-jira-integration-rocks |accessdate=2016-05-06}}</ref> By August 2011, 34 member companies had joined the initiative.<ref name="ZENDESK201108">{{cite news |title=NetworkedHelpDesk.org Welcomes 34 New Member Companies |date=2011-08-12 |url=https://www.zendesk.com/company/press/networkedhelpdesk-org-welcomes-34-new-member-companies/ |accessdate=2016-05-06}}</ref> A year after launching, over 50 organizations had joined.<ref name="ONEYEARLATER">{{cite news |title=NetworkedHelpDesk.org: One Year Later |date=2012-05-31 |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/networkedhelpdeskorg-one-year-later-155961365.html |accessdate=2016-05-06}}</ref> Within Zendesk instances this feature is branded as '''ticket sharing'''.<ref name="ZENDESKTICKETSHARING">{{cite web |title=Share Customer Support Tickets Seamlessly with Zendesk |url=http://www.zendesk.com/product/ticketsharing |date=2011-06-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111028131600/http://www.zendesk.com/product/ticketsharing |archive-date=2011-10-28 |access-date=2016-05-06}}</ref><ref name="LATKIEWICZ2011A">{{cite news |first=Matthew |last=Latkiewicz |date=2011-06-06 |title=Share Support Tickets Across Multiple Zendesks With Our New Ticket Sharing Feature |url=http://www.zendesk.com/blog/zendesk-ticket-sharing-strengthens-collaborative-support |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140122092325/http://www.zendesk.com/blog/zendesk-ticket-sharing-strengthens-collaborative-support |archivedate=2014-01-22 |accessdate=2016-05-06}}</ref><ref name="LATKIEWICZ2011C">{{cite news |first=Matthew |last=Latkiewicz |date=2011-06-06 |title=Networked Help Desk: An Open Standard for Better Customer Service |url=https://www.zendesk.com/blog/networked-help-desk-an-open-standard-for-better-customer-service/ |accessdate=2016-05-06}}</ref>
== Basis == Support tools are generally built around a common paradigm that begins with a customer making a [[ITIL#Request fulfillment|request]] or an [[Incident management (ITSM)|incident]] report, these create a ticket. Each ticket has a progress status and is updated with annotations and attachments. These annotations and attachments may be visible to the customer (public) or only visible to analysts (private). Customers are notified of progress made on their ticket until it is complete. If the people necessary to complete a ticket are using separate support tools, additional overhead is introduced in maintaining the relevant information in the ticket in each tool while notifying the customer of progress made by each group in completing their ticket. For example, if a customer support issue is caused by a software bug and reported to a help desk using one system, and then the fix is documented by the developers in another, and analyzed in a customer relationship management tool, keeping the records in each system up-to-date and notifying the customer manually using a swivel chair approach is unnecessarily time-consuming and error-prone. If information is not transferred correctly, a customer may have to re-explain their problem each time their ticket is transferred.<ref name="FEIL2011"/><ref name="WEINBERGER2011">{{cite news |first=Matthew |last=Weinberger |date=2011-06-07 |title=NetworkedHelpDesk.org: Helping Partners Break Help Desk Barriers? |url=http://talkincloud.com/networkedhelpdesk-org-helping-partners-break-help-desk-barriers |accessdate=2016-05-06}}</ref>
For systems with the Networked Help Desk API implemented, it is possible for several different applications related to a customer's support experience to synchronize data in one uniquely identified shared ticket.<ref name="FINLEY2011C">{{cite journal |title=New API Aims to Unite Customer Service Applications |first=Klint |last=Finley |date=2011-06-07 |url=http://readwrite.com/2011/06/07/customer-service-api/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923233131/http://readwrite.com/2011/06/06/customer-service-api |archivedate=2013-09-23 |accessdate=2016-05-06 |journal=[[ReadWrite]]}}</ref> While many applications in these domains have implemented APIs that allow data to be imported, exported and modified, Network Help Desk provides a common standard for customer support information to automatically synchronize between several systems.<ref name="FEIL2011">{{cite news |first=George |last=Feil |title=Building the Web 3.0: NetworkedHelpDesk |date=2011-06-08 |url=https://blog.newrelic.com/2011/07/08/building-the-web-3-0-networkedhelpdesk/ |accessdate=2016-05-06}}</ref> Once implemented two systems can quickly share tickets with just a configuration change as they both understand the same interface.<ref name="HINCHCLIFFE2011">{{cite journal |title=Enabling collaboration with open APIs |first=Dion |last=Hinchcliffe |date=2011-06-18 |url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/enabling-collaboration-with-open-apis/ |accessdate=2016-05-06 |journal=[[ZDNet]]}}</ref>
Communication between two instances on a specific ticket occurs in three steps, an invitation agreement, sharing of ticket data and continued synchronization of tickets.<ref name="HINCHCLIFFE2011"/> The standard allows for "full delegation" (analysts in both systems each make public and private comments and synchronize status) as well as "partial delegation" where the instance receiving the ticket can only make private comments and status changes are not synchronized.<ref name="ZENDESKTICKETSHARING"/><ref name="API">{{cite web |title=API Walkthough |url=http://networkedhelpdesk.org/api/ |accessdate=2016-05-06}}</ref> Tickets may be shared with multiple instances.<ref name="LATKIEWICZ2011A"/>
