'''PSOLA''' (Pitch Synchronous Overlap and Add) is a digital [[signal processing]] technique used for [[speech processing]] and more specifically [[speech synthesis]]. It can be used to modify the [[pitch (music)|pitch]] and [[duration (music)|duration]] of a speech signal. It was invented around 1986.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Charpentier|first1=F.|last2=Stella|first2=M.|title=Diphone synthesis using an overlap-add technique for speech waveforms concatenation|journal=Acoustics, Speech, and Signal Processing, IEEE International Conference on ICASSP'86.|date=Apr 1986|volume= 11|pages=2015–2018|doi=10.1109/ICASSP.1986.1168657}}</ref>
PSOLA works by dividing the speech waveform in small overlapping segments. To change the pitch of the signal, the segments are moved further apart (to decrease the pitch) or closer together (to increase the pitch). To change the duration of the signal, the segments are then repeated multiple times (to increase the duration) or some are eliminated (to decrease the duration). The segments are then combined using the [[overlap add]] technique.
PSOLA can be used to change the [[Prosody (linguistics)|prosody]] of a speech signal.
==See also== * [[Audio timescale-pitch modification]]
