'''Renewables.ninja'''{{nnbsp}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.renewables.ninja/|title=Renewables.ninja|website=www.renewables.ninja|language=en|access-date=2018-09-20}}</ref> is a web tool developed by [[Imperial College London]] and [[ETH Zürich]] that shows the estimate amount of energy that could be generated by wind or solar farms at any location.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www3.imperial.ac.uk/newsandeventspggrp/imperialcollege/newssummary/news_5-9-2016-16-22-36|title=New tool can calculate renewable energy output anywhere in the world {{!}} Imperial News {{!}} Imperial College London|work=Imperial News|access-date=2018-09-20|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.climateactionprogramme.org/news/new_renewables_ninja_calculates_solar_and_wind_power_availability|title=New 'Renewables ninja' calculates solar and wind power availability - Climate Action Programme|website=www.climateactionprogramme.org|language=en|access-date=2018-09-20}}</ref> The model has been tested by Iain Staffell who is the co{{nbhyph}}developer of renewables.ninja, from the Centre for Environmental Policy at Imperial College London, and Stefan Pfenninger from ETH Zürich to estimate the productivity of all wind farms planned or under construction in Europe for the next 20 years. German electrical supplier [[RWE]] are using it to test their own models of output.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://worldindustrialreporter.com/new-web-tool-helps-monitor-solar-and-wind-energy-worldwide/|title=New Web Tool Helps Monitor Solar and Wind Energy Worldwide - World Industrial Reporter|date=2016-09-07|work=World Industrial Reporter|access-date=2018-09-20|language=en-US}}</ref>

